# viz/index.html

Standalone single-page browser tool for interactively exploring the steno
stroke tree produced by the Rust compiler. It fetches `../out/viz-data.json`
(generated by a separate `viz-data` binary) and renders it as a
click-to-drill-down chip UI, showing a physical keyboard diagram and the
expanded snippet body for whatever node the user has navigated to. No
build step, no dependencies — plain HTML/CSS/JS served over `http://`
(fetch fails under `file://`, hence the error message steering users to
serve the repo root).

The stroke-parsing logic (`parseStroke`, `LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER`)
is a hand-maintained JS port of `crates/steno/src/stroke/keys.rs`'s
`parse_stroke` and bank-order constants — it must be kept in sync manually;
drift here means the keyboard diagram highlights the wrong keys even though
the underlying data is correct. Similarly, `unescapeSnippet` reverses the
LSP-snippet escaping (`\\`, `\$`, `\}`) applied by `esc`/`push_brace` in
`crates/steno/src/snippet/mod.rs` — if that escaping logic changes, this
must change too or literal braces will render with stray backslashes.

Expected JSON node shape: `{ terminal, multiLine, oneLiner, children, axis,
description, oneLinerRoot, synthetic }`. `axis` nodes (from a compiler
"choose one of N variants" construct) aren't rendered directly — `resolve()`
always substitutes the currently-selected option's node instead, and an
axis node's own key is never pushed into `path`. `synthetic` nodes (from
`##>` section grouping) have no real stroke and skip the keyboard/header
rendering entirely.

Navigation state lives in three module-level globals: `path` (only
explicitly clicked keys — singleton children are never stored, they're
recomputed every render via `isSingleton`/auto-chaining in `buildRows()`),
`oneLinerActive` (one global multi-line vs one-liner preference, since
lineflag.rs treats this as a whole-construct choice, not per-stroke), and
`axisSelection` (a `Map` from axis node key to chosen option key, so
choices persist as surrounding rows re-render). `buildRows()` self-heals a
stale `path` by truncating it in place if an upstream axis change made a
stored key no longer valid among current children — this is the only path
mutation outside explicit chip clicks.

`displayKey(key)` substitutes in `currentOneLinerRoot` (the one-liner-
augmented first stroke segment) when one-liner mode is active and the walk
has passed through a node carrying `oneLinerRoot` — this only affects the
displayed stroke text, not the underlying tree key. `variantKeyFor(node)`
picks between `multiLine`/`oneLiner` bodies, preferring the global toggle
only when both exist on a node. The one-liner toggle control itself is
shown only once, at the first row where both variants coexist
(`canShowToggle` / `toggleShown` bookkeeping in `render()`).